\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 So Ida was about a year old when Joseph was born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 No, two. Two. Jos
eph was two years old when I was born. Then - I think there was a difference of about three or four years and then the little boy that mother lost you know. Then there's another three years to my brother Harry. And then from Harry - I think Iris comes nex
t, two years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 So between you and your brother Harry there's quite a long gap?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Yes. Well - well there was one more between us you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 So there's about five years?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Yes, that - yes, that's right, yes, it would be that, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 And then Irish?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Irish next, Iris, Marion and John.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Were they closer as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Well, about two years. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Can you tell me how old your father was when Ida was born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Now - I'll tell you - I don't know whether you can work it out. He died 
- in 1936 and he was sixty-four. My sister died - when she was fifty-five, and she's been dead - let me see, twelve years. She would be - my brother is - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 So she was born in 1910?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 May. No, before that. No, I was born in 1904. And I'm - I - she's four years older than me so she was born in 1900. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 And your father died 1936 when he was sixty-four years old?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 So he must have been about twenty-six or seven when Ida was born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Ida was born, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 He must have been about thirty when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Yes. Yes. Near enough I should say.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Where did he come from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Now - he wasn't a Portland man, he came from - down Haversto}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8747815\charrsid16449734 c}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 k way, that's - down in the country. He - he - he was - I think he was born in -
 now whether he was born in Portland I can't tell you but - his people - his mother is - and they were not Portland people, they were born in the country somewhere around Haverstock or - down in the country somewhere.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 But in Dorset?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Oh yes, in Dorset, yes. Yes, that's right, something like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 What sort of job did he do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 He's a carpenter.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Was he a carpenter all his life?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Yes. Apprentice.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Did he do any other sort of job as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 No. No. All carpentry work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Do you remember your father ever being out of work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 
Yes, my goodness me, that was the cause of all the trouble. Money was very very scarce then. When we were children. When we were growing up. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Who did he work for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Patten. Mr Patten - they - they're well known people in Portland. But the firm Patten, he lives on the hill, lives up at Easton.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 He started off working for him did he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 He learnt his apprenticeship from them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 And he stayed working with them afterwards?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Until - yes, right until - yes, and right up until he died - practically.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Why was he out of work at various times?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Well because there was no work about. You see, when he was a carpenter - there were - it was all handwork, you see. Well then as tim
e came on so they progressed and got - machinery. Quicker, and therefore less work - lots of time. He did the things that the machinery people couldn't do, sort of laying block floors and things like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Was he employed for just specific jobs, specific contracts then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 No. He was employed by this man - all the time - to do, jobs you know like - different jobs.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 But he wasn't actually paid by him all the time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Yes, he was paid by him all the time, he didn't get contract jobs, he was - like - he that was his boss, Mr Bernard Patten.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Did he have regular money coming in then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 
Oh yes. When - when there was work, yes. Yes. Of course when - when there was no work he didn't have any money of course, and there was no such a thing as dole. And there was no such a thing as this Social Security. You see, if it wasn't making money.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 What did he do during those periods?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 He just - did the - perhaps little odd jobs for people round about you know, to earn a few shillings.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Did he ever do anything like fishing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Oh he went on the beach at night time fishing, just luxury you know -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 This wasn't working as a fisherman?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Oh no, no, no, no, no, that was his own private affair. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Do you know how old your mother was when you were born?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 She was - my father was about - six years older.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 He was about twenty-six so she must have been about twenty, twenty-one when Ida was born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Where did she come from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 She came from Weymouth. She was
 a Weymouth woman, yes. She - she was born in Weymouth but she - she - lived nearly all her life at Crediton.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 You say your mother lived at Preston?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Did she work before she married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 No, no. No, I don't think so, I don't know what she did - before she was married.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Did she do any work after she was married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 No. No. It was a full time job looking after the family.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Did she do any part time work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 No. No. No, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Can we now talk about your life at home while you were a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 
Well - as a child. Yes well - well it was a very happy childhood although of course as I say money was very scarce then you know, and - we didn't have very many luxuries. But - we got over all right and - we had - tuppence a week pock
et money. And we could buy - a lot of things with this tuppence. I used to - a farthing to get in the pictures, I used to spend my tuppence in going to the pictures therefore I didn't have any sweets, but if I didn't want to go I used to spend a penny on 
M
onday and a penny on Wednesday. You see? Well if I wanted to spend it on sweets I couldn't go to the pictures. If I went to the pictures I had no sweets. I used to spend a penny on Monday, and a penny on Wednesday. And I used to get an awful lot of sweets
 
for a penny. Great big bagful of - sweets. Well then - that was that, but - if we went any errands, we weren't allowed to take any money from anyone for going errands, we used to get a piece of cake or a piece of bread and jam. Yes. And - there was no beg
ging - when we were living in King Street, there was no begging, we used to take in washing and my mother used to say, now}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8747815\charrsid16449734  you go down and see if granny}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 's - washing is ready. And we used to go down, take it to wherever she had to - wherever it had to go and - she'd say, now don't you dare take a penny. You weren't allowed to take anything for any message for old people.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 You had your own pocket money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Yes. That was that and we had to make - we couldn't ask for any more, we wouldn't get it. And we 
also - my mother was very strict as regards - going out. We were allowed out to play an hour after school. Summer - and winter time and perhaps a little bit later summertime when it was light.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 This is from when you were five?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Onwards. Well when 
- I left school - in 1914 when I left school I was fourteen you see, 1914. Well, if you reckon that up that comes to - about - just before '18 doesn't it? Well - the boys were away at the war. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Is that house in Artists now a big house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Well,
 it had got - it had got four bed - two bedrooms. Now wait a minute, four - three bedrooms and an attic - in Artist Row. And in King Street it was - just the same, three bedrooms and an attic. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 So your mother and father had one room did they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 
And then we divided up into the rest. Yes. Yes. When - when I went - when they - there was no electric, it was all oil lamps. There was no electric at all. Oil lamps.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 So there was just your parents and your brother and sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 YES.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Did you have any relatives with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Oh no, no, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Or any lodgers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Oh no, no, no. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Did your mother have anybody to come in and help her with the work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 No. No. No, not a bit, she had to do that herself.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Did she do all the washing herself?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Yes, washing and ironing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Did your mother or father make your clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 
My mother used to make our clothes - occasionally, you know. But - she was very at that sort of thing, she would - cut up something to make a frock for -
 or some like that. Yes, make up - make up clothes, well she had to because I mean there wasn't the money coming in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Would she buy the material?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 No. Well sometimes she would buy the material. But - nearly always she would cut down you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Where would she get the clothes from then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Well - perhaps - something she'd - of her own clothing. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 It wouldn't be clothes from other people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Oh no, she didn't have clothes from other people, no, it was just her own clothing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 She didn't go to jumble sales?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 
No. There wasn't very much you see. No. You might occasionally get one but very very few, very - seldom. You see, people couldn't - do it. They couldn't throw out like they do today. I mean they - and with shoes, well, if 
you paid - twelve shillings for a pair of shoes you were - you had a good pair, you were like a queen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Did your father mend your shoes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Yes. Yes, he did a lot of mending, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Did he make shoes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 No, he didn't make them, no, he just me
nded them you know, put - new soles and that on them, if they weren't gone too far but of course, you know children, if they - they kick them out -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Did you buy new shoes then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Oh yes. In a shop, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Did your mother get any clothes from relatives?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 
Well no, you see, everybody was in the same boat. You see. I mean, if - it wasn't a question of saying, oh - I've finished with this, you can have it. They had to wear it to the bitter end, because there was no money forthcoming. I mean,
 it wasn't only one, and - you see, my brother, Joe - during the strike of 1926, he was out of work for four years. And my father had to keep him. And he couldn't go and get any money for him anywhere. See, there was no work about and it was just - it was
 unlucky.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Where did you actually buy your clothes, here in Portland?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 In Portland, yes. In Portland, different shops.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Was there a local shop for the shoes as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Oh there were - I suppose there were only about three shops, local shop
s, Stones, Thriftsbys and - I don't remember the other one. No, I can't remember.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 They came from shops rather than your mother belonging to clubs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Oh yes, no clubs. Well there weren't any clubs about then, well there were I suppose but the - not as it is now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 She didn't sort of save money in a shop?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 
No, no, no. Well she'd say, well - when we were growing up - well, Iris must get a pair of shoes this week, you see, and in about a couple of weeks time somebody else would have to have a pair of shoes, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Did you have special clothes for special occasions?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Oh no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Would there be any special occasion when you'd have new clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Only - well, we always - my mother always tried to get us something - Whitsun. You know
, Whit Sunday. Make our dresses or something for Whit Sunday. And we were - they were - had to go to chapel. I used to belong to the Wesleyan chapel then but I'm church now. But - we used to have to go Sunday morning, Sunday afternoons and chapel at night
. And - I skipped chapel once and - put the penny in my shoe and forgot to take it out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 What happened?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 
Well - my mum found the penny and there was a - good hiding. Very strict. And if she caught us you know - it was not a question of - wait a min
ute, I'm coming, if she called us we had to be there or else. And if she didn't come she'd say, I called you. I shan't call you again. And that was that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Would she do it with her hand?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Cane. Had to go to the shop and buy the cane too.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Did you have it on your hand?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Yes. On your bottom. You know. Yes, she used to say - there used to be a little shop at the bottom of our street called Sampson}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8747815\charrsid16449734 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 s, they used to have these canes with a crook hand. Yes. She'd say, go up Sampson}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8747815\charrsid16449734 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 s and get a ca
ne and they were a ha'penny. And when we got back we had the hiding for it, for what we - hadn't done right. If that's not punishment I don't know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Did you have a hiding very often or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Yes, I was the one that had 'em all. My brothers and sis
ters were too frightened to say anything but - I was the one that just - you know, took the - took a chance, that's what it was. Just taking a chance. I remember once my brother - my mother had saved up and she bought my brother a new suit. And he went on
 
a top of a - street, across the road and up these steps. And she was - she said - she went out to the gate and she looked up and she saw John running the bank. She said, come here. And she gave him the biggest hiding of his life because he was rolling in 
the dirt, with his new suit on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Did your father ever punish you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 
No. He couldn't - he couldn't punish us, he - he - if he started he started laughing, he couldn't do anything. That's how my mother had to take over. And she'd say to him, can't you
 talk to these children, and he'd say, no. That sort of thing you know. And she said, well you are stupid. And he'd say, oh I'll leave that to you. And that's what she - she made up for it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 How did you get on with your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Oh fine, fine. And my mother you know. She was very - they were very good, they were always there. Always there when you wanted them.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Did your father help your mother with any of the jobs in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Did he help with anything like cleaning or cooking or washing up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 No, no, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Did your mother do all these things?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 My mother, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 How about making a fire?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 He could often light the fire sometimes, of course there was no - I mean, it was all - Rinse it in cold water, and then
 rinse it again in blue water. And then put it through the mangle. You know, old fashioned mangle. But it always went through the blue water. And perhaps - a little bit of starch in the blue water.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Did your mother have a special day to do the washing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 
Well - she used to do Mondays and Tuesdays. And then - ironing - when she could, because I mean there was a family of you see and then the ironing and - then - perhaps - Thursday she'd do the bedrooms.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Did you help with the washing, you and your sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Gosh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Did you have to help?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 
I had to help, don't worry. When I was about seventeen - I used to - my brothers used to work in the dockyard and their clothes were filthy. And I used to have a rubbing board, in the big bath you
 know, a rubbing board and a scrub - scrubbing brush, and scrub all the - what you call it - and then pop them in the copper - to boil. And then - as you say, rinse them in cold water and rinse them in blue. I used to -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 This is when you were about seventeen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 
Yes. And we - we had to hang clothes, our - all our washing out the front because there was no - there was no back to the houses. We had our washing all out in the front on the line, on the clothes line. Yes. 'Cos there's no - there was no ba
ck there you see, they all had to use the front.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Did you help when you were younger?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 
Oh - well you see I was the - my sister - my eldest sister was in service, and - I was the next eldest girl. And then - and then there were two boys after that.
 You see, then the other girls came - later on in life, and - they had an easy time, they didn't know what it was to do anything. They had a glorious time. But the first - my sister and my - my other sister and myself and my brother had a hard time. Becau
se - work was very very scarce, my father was out of work a lot, and - you see - we just had to make do. My brother was out of work, you know that slump, 1926. He was in that, he was out of work for four years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Your sister was only about four years older than you wasn't she?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Yes, yes, that's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 When you were about five or six or seven did you have any jobs like this to help around the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Well, I used to sort of - wash up and - do things like - set the table and things like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 You didn't have to help with the washing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Oh no. Not when I was tiny.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Did your father help with decorating the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 No, my mother used to do all the papering. Yes. My father - my mum always used to do all the decorating and paperi
ng and painting. My father was a carpenter, he was that, but he never used to do it - anything. He never used to do anything in the house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 What repairs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Oh, well if there was any repairs to be done, yes, he used to do that, but not very often, h
e - he - he used to say - all right, I'll - see to that later on. You know, that later on never came.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Was it your own house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 No, we - no, no, we rented that one, in - in King Street, but that was our own house in Artist Row, family house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 This is the one that your grandfather was living in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 
Yes. And my brother lives in now. He married, he married and they - lived in the house because - when my mother died - my father died and left the house - and whatever there was to her. When she die
d she didn't make a will. You see? And - I happened to be in South Africa at the time and they wrote and said that - they'd given Joe the house. They let Joe have the house. And - providing that it could be a home for anybody that wanted it. You see?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Did your father do any improvements then to that house in Artist Row?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 
Oh no. No, the - the one in Artist Row - is - well it's been re-done, it's beautiful now. But the one in King Street - was a - a little house, little - rooms, you know, tiny rooms 
and - a sort of a - narrow stairway with bent up the top you know, one of those houses. An attic with a little window.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Do you remember him when you were a child doing things in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Yes. Well just -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Improving things, building cupboards?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Oh no, no, no we didn't - there was - there was - there was no space for that sort of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Did he go and do things in your grandfather's house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Well no, because - you see my grandfather's house was - at that time - it was a double fr
onted house and it was two small house - rooms, one either side and those up the - bed - and a big attic across the top, you see. But they were all in built in cupboards. You see, so there was no need. In the - in the kitchen - I did - I think they did ta
k
e a cupboard away - and make a bookshelf underneath. But there was cupboards with doors you know. And - summertime it was infested with ants. You couldn't - you couldn't do anything. I mean you couldn't - you couldn't stop them because we had a little tin
y garden in the front, and - I think that's where they came from. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Did your father do things for you children, did he dress you in the mornings or undress you at night at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Well if - if my mum - if my - my mother suffered with asthma. Yes.
 And - sometimes she had to stay in bed for a day or something, then he - he'd say - he'd - see that we had our breakfast in the morning and see that we were ready for school. When we were tiny you know. And of course as we got older we could help ourselv
es a little bit.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 So if your mother was ill?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 
Oh yes, he'd take over. He took over and - yes. I mean he wasn't a man to go out - evening time. He used to - I'll tell you what he used to do. He used to come home from work, and he'd come - he'd go ov
er to see his father, when grandma died, 'cos grandma died years and years and years before grandpa. And he'd go over to grandpa's house and he'd say - then he'd come back and he'd say to my mother, oh that silly old man, he wants to go fishing. And the t
i
de is not right until three o'clock tomorrow morning. The silly old thing. Suppose I'd better go. So - he used to get up and go fishing. Three o'clock in the morning. Then he'd come home - have a couple of hours sleep or an hours sleep and then go to work
. Sometimes they'd catch a fish and sometimes they didn't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Was this actually going out in a boat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 No. On the beach, sitting on the pebbles. No, not off of the boat.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Did these happen when you were quite young?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Oh yes, when I was young,
 about - oh I suppose about - ten, eleven, twelve I suppose. And - when they caught a fish, used to catch bass over there, and sometimes they'd catch - big ones, you know, sometimes, great big ones. Well - dozens of times - they - I've - got a great big m
eat dish, and grandpa has - cleaned it. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8747815\charrsid16449734 Ju}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 
st gutted it you know, not took the head off, just gutted it. I've been up to the burn, up to the officers mess and sold it. For about seven and six. And of course that was - a lot of money then. And the same with t
he County Naval Canteen. Grandpa would say, you take it down to the Naval Canteen, down to the officers - there and - down - I used to go down there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 This would be your grandfather's money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Oh - now, we didn't get any. We didn't even get anything for our trouble. 'Cos it had to go in the house. Oh dear.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Would your grandfather give some of it to your parents then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Oh yes, oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Was this the sort of thing that happened when your father was unemployed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Well, yes, he would if 
he - he had the chance but - I mean - he was more or less - out looking for work all the time you see. You see, as I told you, he was a carpenter. And - it was all right when he was young, a carpenter, he was a good carpenter. And my grandpa was a shipwri
ght carpenter. Worked in the dockyard. And - but when machinery came in of course they - hand carpentry wasn't wanted. 'Cos it - you see, the - mass production and that - turned it right out. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Did your father do very much with you children? Did he read to you in the evenings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 
Oh no, no, no. No, he - he didn't, he wasn't a man like that, he was a very homely man, and - he used to come home from work, and - wash and have his tea, and as I say of over to see his father, come back and perhaps look
 at the paper but - he was there - always there. He - he didn't do anything but he was always there. Never - he all - you could count on him being - you'd say, where's daddy? And he's gone}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8747815\charrsid16449734  t}
{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 o see grandpa. He won't be long. And he'd be back.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Do you remember him ever playing games with you or reading stories or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 
No, I don't - I think we used to play draughts and things like that you know and he used to play sometimes and that but - I don't think - he - he loved his children and a
ll that but I don't think he was a man that - could adapt himself to entertain sort of thing. Of course you see - he was - you must understand - those days - the working man was the head of the house and - and then he wanted peace and quiet when he came h
ome, you see. That's the way, exactly. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Do you remember him taking you out on your own without your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Oh we used to go - yes, he's taken us - Sunday afternoons he used to take us for a walk. And - and perhaps mum wasn't very well and t
hat and then he'd take us all up round - round the - what we used to call the railroad. And that's - you know where that is don't you. Well we used to come round - go up one way and come round the other, we used to come - go}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8747815\charrsid16449734  past the town, walk up the in-}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 l
ine right round and down round the other way. Or else we'd go up - by the council office, up that road. Right through the churchyard, right out the - Bracknor Fort and walk round again. Of course you see there was no buses there. You couldn't get a bus, y
o
u - you couldn't say, oh we'll hop on a bus. There were no buses, and if you wanted to go - there used to be a man by the name of Hoskins. And he used to have a horse and - dray, you know, horse and cart, he was a - a - that used to take people round sigh
tseeing. But - he'd get up his load and he'd charge so much and he'd take them all round, all out the Bill and all round on this horse and cart.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Was it just an open cart?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Like a hay}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8747815\charrsid16449734 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 wagon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Yes, that's right, something like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Was he a Portland man?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Yes. Hoskins his name was. I don't - I think he used to live down High Street, at the time. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Was the railway here then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Oh railway, yes. Oh -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 You've got the railway track there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 No, that - tha
t was the - the stone used to go down there. You know - now let me see, you know when we come across the bridge don't you. Yes, down - down the incline. You know, down - you can go - go down and come out Castletown, don't you, well - stone used to go down
 
there - you see. Well - we used to - oh when we were kids we used to sit on the - the - truck that was coming up empty. And the other one was going down loaded you see, like the pulley. Dozens of times we've been sat on there and had a ride up to the top.
 
And I'll tell you another thing - down at the old castle there used to be an old - Colonel or Captain or somebody lived down the - down the - castle, belonging to the firm. And he used to come in the mornings and then people were concerned with stone - us
ed to put a sa}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8747815\charrsid16449734 c}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 k for him to sit on and he used to ride up to the burn - on that truck rather than walk. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 I didn't realize they were still using that stone quarry, that incline at this stage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Well they don't use it for stone, 'cos it's all fi
nished. Oh yes, they do - oh yes, oh yes, yes. Of course the - the - the horses used to come - bring the - the sone round from - you know - Priory Corner do you? You know when you go up - you know when you go up - instead of coming up the burn hill you go
 
up the other hill, up the other road, when you get round the top, when you get up to the top that's called Priory Corner, you see? Well now, the stone used to come - to that edge - that - on a truck. And the horses used to bring it right round - right rou
n
d to the - old rectory, you know where the old rectory is don't you? - Right, right round - right round until they got to the bridge - until they got to the house. And then they used to unlace the horses, and put the stone - down the - by the pulleys. The
r
e used to be a man on the - we used to call it the White House, man up there - you know, sort of operating from there, bringing the - empty one up, taking the full one down. And when the full one got down to the bottom, the rail - this railway rails - I -
 
I don't think they're still there. And - they used to go - run, shunt - at they used to say, shunt and run. Now the stone mine used to say, go to the - station and he used to say to the man, I want one shunt today, or two shunts, that meant, he want two e
n
gines to - two lots of the engine twice to shunt the stone so that it could be carted away by barge. Then they - they used to go right onto the quayside, then the cranes used to lower the big - great big stones right - you know, big stones right into the 
barge. And take them off that way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 When did they stop doing this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 
Oh - they haven't been doing - they stopped doing - now let me see - I was nineteen - eighteen or nineteen when they stopped - the horses. But then - they used to have a big tracti
on engines - down - used to come from the quarries - loaded up, oh I suppose, great big pieces of stone you know, two pieces on one truck, they've got two trucks. And the wheels were like that, the traction engine, and they used to go down Fortunes Well. 
Down to Castletine. And Fortunes Well was just like a churn, it - it was mud. Not like it is now. And when it was raining - it was - just like walking through a mud pond.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Right down through the main street?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Right through the main street, yes. No,
 no. I - Sunday nights, when we children, when I - well, children, I suppose I was - what was I, about seventeen, eighteen, and - you couldn't move for - in Fortunes Well of a Sunday night. The people walking up and down. Crowded.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Come from all over the island?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 
Yes. You - you go up the road, you go up the top of the - what - you meet somebody, have a little matter. You turn round and come back. They might come back with you or they might not. And then - you walk - that's all they did, used to wal
k up and down, walk up and down. Nothing else to do, nowhere else to go. In Fortunes Well. Might - might wander off down to Castletown but it was very very rare - went down there.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 They didn't come to go to church there at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Chapel, they'd go
 to chapel. Church and chapel. I used to go to chapels, I could go if I - remember once I didn't go, I put the penny in me shoe, for me collection. And I took - I forgot it and took it off, I had a - beating for it because I told a lie. Then, you see, we 
used to go to - chapel at six o'clock, come out at half past seven. And I was allowed out until half past eight or nine o'clock.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 How old were you then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Just - fifteen, sixteen. And - woe betide me if I was late.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 What would happen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 I wa
sn't allowed out next week. My poor friend used to try and get it, she used to say, Mrs Gail, is Evelyn coming out? No, she's not coming out, and if you come again I'll throw a bucket of water over you. And I used to do - I used to learn music. And I used
 to be in the front room perhaps practicing and Kitty comes in the window and - I used to say to her, see you in a minute. My mother say, no, you won't see her in a minute. I didn't know she was there. Oh dear.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 So she was quite strict then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Oh my mother was very strict. Very strict.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Was she with all of you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 
Yes, all of us, oh very strict. I remember my brother once - he had a - of course it was hard job to get clothes you know when there wasn't much money. And my mother used to save and
 save and she bought John a suit. And she came out - went out to the gage to see somebody and she happened to look up the road, and he was up the steps - I don't know whether you know where King Street is, do you? Well, just right opposite there's some ho
u
ses with some steps up. Well there used to be - Mrs Reed used to live up there and - she saw John, on the floor, on the ground, with his best suit on. And she said, Evelyn. Go and get your brother. Oh dear. John, your mum wants you. Come down and she leat
h
ered him. She said, I'll give you, she said, rolling in the dirt, she said, when I've struggled to keep you tidy. She leathered him, she - he had to go out in his old clothes after that. Oh she was ever so strict. That - if I - she called me and I'd say -
 
what? She'd say, what did you say? I called you. Yes, mummy. That's better. No more. And if she said, come here. And if she was talking to anybody and we went - she'll say, well? Just like that. Inside. We knew. And when we got in she'll say, I don't know
 
how many times I've told - you've got to be told but don't come near me when I'm talking to anyone, don't be so rude. And the next time she said, I shan't speak, I shall - she said, I shall act. She was ever so strict. Well she had to be. Because my fathe
r was so lenient. You see, my - I - as I said to my - of course - the pictures then you could go to pictures for - tuppence. I had three}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8747815\charrsid16449734  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 pence a week. If I wanted to go to the pictures for tuppence I had a penny to spend, if I wanted a - if I spent a penny 
for pictures, go right at the back I had tuppence to spend. That had to last me until the next week. You see?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Was this in Fortunes Well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Well, the picture house was where the bus stop is down - by the - down the square. Masonic Hall. That was t
he picture house. Anyway - if I say to my father - daddy, can I go to the pictures? And he'll say, I don't know, I haven't got any money. And he'll say, in any case what did your mummy say? No. So it is, he - he wouldn't go against her you see. But if I s
aid, well she didn't say anything, and he'll say, oh all right, go on. You know. It wouldn't do for my mum to have been - lenient with us 'cos we could do what we liked with our dad.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 You only went to the pictures when she said you could go then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Was there a particular time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Saturdays.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 How old were you when you started going to the pictures?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Oh about - eight I suppose. Yes but then you see - it wasn't in the evening time, it was afternoon. See, it was that matinee. And
 she used to say - you be here - at five o'clock. In this house at five o'clock. You hear me don't you? YES.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Did you have any tasks that you had to carry out regularly at home to help your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 No, no, one task Friday nights we used to have to do. We - no, we didn't - only just wash up dishes. We -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 You always washed the dishes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 
Always - teatimes. Wash the dishes up. And - bath - on Saturdays, in front of the fire with a big long bath, 'cos we had no bathrooms you know. See. And ther
e were six of us to bath. I used to say, I'll go first, because - if I - you see, my mum, she - what she used to do she used to put a handful of soda in the water. Get the copper boiling. Yes. Couldn't do anything else. You see. Get the water boiling. A h
a
ndful of soda - because the water's very hard in Portland. And - right - and we used to have - she used to wash our hair in the bath. And rinse it. And I used to say, I want to be first because - my hair was long, I had black hair right down here, and - s
h
e used to wash my hair and let it dry a bit, brush it and plait it. You see. And - that was all right 'cos I could curl up with my book then. It didn't matter about anything else, I could - I could read while the others were being bathed. You see. Well - 
t
hen - that was Saturday nights. And we were all ready for - Sunday school Sunday morning. Sunday morning Sunday school, Sunday afternoon, Sunday evening. I used to go to Wesleyan chapel until I was about twelve, and then - they didn't have anything organi
sed for - sort of a social evening, they used to have Band of Hope when I was about five, six, but that went, nobody sort of seemed - interest - be interested. And then we went to - St Johns church. And they formed and Girls Friendly Society. And that -

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Which is the Wesleyan chapel?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 At Brackenbury. Yes. And - and then - I joined the church there because of the Girls Friendly - and I've been church ever since.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 This is the one in the main street?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 St Johns. No, but I was going to say, thi
s Friday night task - there used to be an old lady by the name of Granny Wentworth, and she was a very old lady and she used to have to take in washing to make ends meet. And my mother used to say to us, go down to Granny Wentworth's, get her washing, tak
e
 it up to the top of - King Street, and wait for her. We used to wait and poor old Granny used to be about half an hour sometimes getting up there you know. And you know what kiddies are, you know, we used to get so impatient. Still we had to do it. And t
hen we say - where are we going to go Granny? And she'll say, oh so and so, and we take it. And bring the basket back. And my mother said, if I catch you take a ha'penny from that old lady, she says, I'll leather you. We had to do it. That was our - duty.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Did you get anything at home for doing this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 No. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Did you have anything to do at home apart from the washing up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Did you have to do anything for your younger brothers and sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Might clean their shoes for them 
you know, like - younger ones but - you see - there were so - there was - you see - my brother is - five - four years younger than me I think he is. Yes. And - I used to have to stay in with him, sort of - if my mum was going out anywhere to a meeting or 
anything I used to have to baby}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8747815\charrsid16449734 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 
sit with him. Because my mum would never left us on our own. Never went out and left us you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 This is when you were older, when you were about thirteen or fourteen?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Yes, that's right, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Do you remember having to dress him or undress him or feed him when he was a baby at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 No, no, my mother always did - always did all that, she never left it - left us to do that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 There were several younger ones fairly close together weren't there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Yes
, well then - then you see the next one was - well Iris was next I think. Iris is fifty - no, I think John - we lost a little brother. 'Cos I was - John - Joe is - Harry is - sixty -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 She lost one after you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 YES - no, either after me or after John - I'm not sure. Now I can't be sure about that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 You were born about 1904 and Harry was born about 1910?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Then Iris about 1912?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Yes, that's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Marion about two years after that, and John about two years after that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Yes. Then there was Marion is the youngest one, she's - well - getting on for fifty I suppose she is.. That's the youngest one.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 I thought John was the youngest?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2101778\charrsid16449734 No, M}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 arion's the youngest.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Did you have to go to bed at a certain time when you were young, did you have a regular bedtime?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 
Yes, we used to have to be in bed by - half past - eight summertime and eight o'clock wintertime. No light - had to go to bed, there were no lights.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 How old would you have been?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Oh I suppose ab
out - twelve I suppose, thirteen. I - I was quite early - quite you know - old to get into bed. When I was - when I left school - fourteen, I wasn't allowed out - any - any - half past seven summertime - wintertime and half past eight winter - summertime,
 had to be in by - indoors at half past eight.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Was this different from your friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 
I don't know, they - well - near enough the same because they were - we were all the - same sort of families you see, I mean, they are - you never - they never 
ran the streets, you never - I - I tell you, I - summer holidays - we used to be allowed - outside the house - later. But not in the street. We could stay outside until about nine o'clock because it was light. Skipping. Playing hopscotch. That - that was 
o
ur - games. But not away from the house. That was - just for holidays but - when we went to school we had to be in bed - early. And there was no - no - no lights, you couldn't say, oh well, we'll take a book and go to bed. 'Cos we didn't have electric, we
 had candles. Yes. You see. And my mum would never let us read by candlelight because of our eyesight. It wasn't good you see. If we put the - if we took the candle and let it burn for a little while it was - put that light out, put that candle out.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Did you share a bedroom with your sister?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 
Oh yes, we had to, we - we used to be - Ida - no, not Ida, she was away. Used to be - the bosy, we - had to sleep on a - in a - little bed}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2101778\charrsid16449734 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 chair, you know, sort of a - cot thing. Not a cot but a - sort of - sam
e kind of thing, and the two boys in the big bed. We used to share - there used to be - two boys in one bed. And - I used to sleep on the side, and then there used to be the other boys up in the attic. Oh yes, it was - all the family shared three bedrooms
. And mum and dad had the front bedroom you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 So you actually remember sharing a bed with your sister?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Oh yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 And with Ida when you were smaller?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 YES, I remember once my brother - my grandfather - my - Uncle Joe, he was a sai
lor and he - he brought home some ships cocoa. You know the - do you know ships cocoa at all? Haven't you ever seen it? Well it's a big block. And it's thick chocolate like that and you cut it up, you know. It's delicious. Oh it was - well we used to have
 
this - this - had a block in the - in the - food cupboard. And somebody pinched it see. Well I happened to be sleeping between Ida and Joe at the time. And my mother came upstairs and she said, who had the ships cocoa? Nobody answered, bang, crash wallop 
with a strap. I didn't catch any 'cos I was so small, it was these two, I didn't get any of it. Joe had it, yes. Joe had it. He - he - he owned up, he had it. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 I suppose all sorts of high jinks went on?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 At what age do you remember putting yourself to bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 
Oh - I - what - actually - oh about eight - eight or - oh about eight or nine years old I suppose. Used to go out and - she used to say - here's a candle. Get into bed. I remember once - I - thought myself, oh well I'm 
going to - 'cos I - I was a terrible one for - for - in - where the paper shop now is it was - Sampson this name when I was a little girl, Mr Sampson. And I used to go up there and I used to get penny fairytale books. You know, they were - little ones lik
e
 that. Only a penny. And - if they were a bit soiled I used to have them for a ha'penny. And I used - one day I thought, if I put a coat under the door our mum won't see that light. But I forgot the crack at the side and the top. So I was reading there an
d she came up and she said - I thought I told you to put this light out. No, she said, have you put your light out? Yes mummy. I thought myself, she won't know. She did though. She ran out - oh dear.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 What did she do, do you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Just say, oh
 put your light out or else I shall be up there. That's all there was to it. Put your light out or else I'll be there. And it was - you know. And it was a - wasn't a - as I told you it wasn't a question of - calling and not coming. Call you and you were t
h
ere - or else. Yes. And if she said to me - I want you to go up the street, and I said, oh. I want you to go to the street, go up and do some shopping. And she'd give me a list and - me money and off I'd go and I daren't say, oh I don't want to go. Can't 
someone else go? No fear.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Was this a regular thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 
Oh yes. We - we did, yes, we used to do a lot of shopping for her because - now sometimes she would have an attack of asthma and - she couldn't breathe you know, it was terrible. Awful it was, I
've seen her - holding the bedpost like this, trying to get her breath back you know. And we used to give a list and - and you - you daren't say, they haven't got so and so. I know they've got it, I've seen it at the shop, and you just go back and get it.
 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Was it anybody in particular's job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 
No. Well, no, she'd say - oh some - she'll say, oh you went - you went up the street after school yesterday. Come on Harry. My brother Harry and I could never agree. As children. And really nasty we were 
to one another. And - she used to do some cleaning up at the bank, Topson Boyds Bank then, Mrs - and the people's name were de Gruchy. And - we were in the yard there and - he upset me or something and he I chopped his fingers down like that. She had to g
o - had to go up and fetch her. Oh dear, dear.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 She had a little job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Cleaning, yes. Cleaning yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Was this just one morning a week or something like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 I - I don't know, I think there was - no, it's two or three mornings a week. Up there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 This is when you were a bit older?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 
Well, yes, it was. I wasn't very old then. I couldn't have been very old because - I should think I was about nine, ten. Well she had to do something you see 'cos dad was out of work so much.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Did she have any other sort of jobs like this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 
No. No. No, she couldn't do anything else, no, she only did that you know like when dad was out of work and then - and then when dad got - work she stopped it. She was just a help out you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Was there any other way that she could get money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 No. No doel you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Did the family help?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 
No, well there was - I mean she - she only had - she had no brothers and she only had sisters and they weren't in Portland. And my - my father didn't have a
ny sisters. You see, he only had brothers, and they were married and away. There were only three of them you see, three brothers. And my mum had - three - two sisters of her own and - four stepsisters.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Did you have clean clothes at a particular time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Oh yes, we used to have - we could - we changed all our clothes on Saturday. Yes, you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 You were clean then for the whole week?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Oh well - now, we used to like - like clean clothes, and then - you always had - clean pants like two or th
ree times a week you see, I mean there wasn't a question of wearing a pair of pants for a week. And - we used to wear - at school, when I went to school when I was five, we used to wear - aprons with embroidery down the front and - goffered sleeves. Goffe
r
ed. You know with a - you never heard of it? Haven't you? Well, years ago - people like - very old people, specially Portland people, you get a goffering iron and something like - curling tongs, you know. And - you - they always starch - Portland people a
r
e terrible for starching stuff. I don't know whether you are, but they do, they starch an awful lot. And - they used to have frills on their pillowcases you know, all kind of frills, and they used to - heat the iron and - how the goffered is they'd do it 
l
ike that and turn it, see, and - and turn it like that all the way along, and then it used to give it that crimp. And then they used to - we used to have great big sleeves, you know, sort of - not a wing sleeve, just like - piece about here. Along our pin
afore, and they used to be - starched and goffered. And all embroidery all down the front.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Did your mother do the embroidery herself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 No, you buy then. Used to buy them. Yes, buy the pinafores. Embroidery pinafores, but you never see it now. And
 you never see child - babies with tie-ups on their - gowns do you. Tie ups. NO. When - when the children - when the babies are born, they used to wear - a vest, a binder - a flannelette back}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8598532\charrsid16449734 
-}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 wrap, that was - a thing - a long thing, and a flannel back}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8598532\charrsid16449734 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 
wrap
. And that used to - be - they used to fold it over, be - if - therefore it was long, and then they used to double it up and pin it either side, you see. And then - they had the long gown. On. And then used - for a little boy it was blue tie-ups and a - t
hey used to gather the sleeves up like that, and tie them, there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Like a little bow?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 That's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Was this peculiar to Portland?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 No. It was a general thing, general thing, yes. But - you never see backwraps and binders and things like
 that now. Gosh no, I've still got a - I've got a - somewhere at home, I've got a - a long gown that belonged to - a man in Portland when he was a little boy - when he was a baby, and that was fifty years old and I expect it's a hundred years old now. Chr
istening gown. All embroidered all - with it's embroidery all down. And that's got tie-up sleeves.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Were they full length sleeves?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 No, no, no. Just a tiny - gathered - you know, puffed sleeve. Yes. Yes, and tied up with a piece of blue for a boy a
nd a piece of pink for a girl. And you see they never used to shorten them until - my brother Joe - he was in petticoats until he was three years old. Yes. Yes. Never used to shorten them, never used to britch them until they were about four. Petticoats. 
N
ow they - they don't put them in anything else but - they put them short clothes straight away. They never have all these back wraps and things like that. 'Cos it wasn't healthy. Do you know babies never used to see daylight when they were born, taken out
 the first time they used to have a shawl. A head shawl, a shawl and a veil over the top. And - for three days. Wasn't allowed to see daylight. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Were there any other particular sort of clothes you remember that you had?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 No, I don't think so, just ordinary clothes you know, I mean -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 What did you have to go to church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 
Oh just a - a - hat and coat you know, just a - perhaps we - oh had a best dress you know, a special dress. Something or other and a - Whitsun - always had a dress - wh
ite dress made. Whit Sunday. Always had - Whit Sunday, a white dress. White shoes and stockings. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Did you make special hats?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 No, I - I - they did make special hats but I never used to wear very much, 'cos I never wore a hat, very - very seld
om. Sometimes I - I wore - I remember once my mother bought a - a - big leghorn hat you know, a straw hat, leghorn, and - had a big satin bow and I thought I was the Queen of Sheba. 'Cos this bow was laid on the brim, the brim was wide you know and it lai
d just flat and it was beautiful really. And it was a very expensive hat but - that was the only thing - only hat I can remember - wearing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 How old were you then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Oh I'd be about - fourteen - thirteen or fourteen when I - 'cos I went to Sunday school, went to church quite until I was quite old. Yes.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Where did the family have their meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 In the kitchen. Well you see, there was only a - a front room, a kitchen and a scullery there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Was there any occasion when you ate in the other room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Very rarely unless Sundays - perhaps Sundays we might, you know - go in there, but very rare.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 What was the front room used for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Well just for - anyone used to come - we used to - sort of - have our meal}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8598532\charrsid16449734  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 and then go and sit in there in the evening or something like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 It was used by the family thought?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Oh yes. Always used by the family, yes. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Where did your mother cook?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Well - she had a - a - kitchen stove. Old fashioned kitchen - a fire and the oven at the side, yes. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Was it coal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Coal, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 What was it like cooking on that, do you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Oh - yes. Cooked dozens of times - and - and I used to like cooking and - they were terrible to keep clean, awful.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Did it have to be black}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8598532\charrsid16449734 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 leaded?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Black}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8598532\charrsid16449734 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 
leaded and - and shone with a brush and then a - and in - in the front you know, the front of the fire - place there used to be steel plate, that used to be burnished, with a burnishing steel.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Who used to do this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 
Oh sometimes we did and some - oh there's another job we used to have to do, every Saturday. One - one week we would do - one would do the knives - on a knife board and brick dust. And then - then the - somebody else had to do the spoons and forks. Clean 
them. Well the one -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 What were they cleaned with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Metal polish. YES. But the one that did the - spoons that last week did the knives this week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Which job did you prefer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Well I don't know, I - I think I - I think I liked the knives bec
ause - when you did the metal polish you had to wash 'em and dry them. And the knives you see used to rub up and - rub them up and down, have you seen a knife board? YES. Put the brick}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8598532\charrsid16449734 -}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 dust on and rub 'em up and down like this, you see, and get them all sh
iny. And then - get a clean cloth and wiped all the brick dust off, whether it stuck there or not it - it was another thing but - if you were caught you know and didn't wash them you were always - well we used to try and get away with it believe you me - 
o
nce I - we had to wash up. It was my turn to wash up in the evening, and - there was a - a - enamel pie dish, and - I didn't want to wash it so I pushed it under the sink, see, and - and - my mum - came out to the bottom of the stairs, 'cos we had stair d
o
or you see with a latch. She opened the door and she said, who washed up tonight? Nobody answered. She said. I said who washed up tonight? I did mummy. Well - what about the pie dish that's still here? Oh - come on. Down. I had to go down and wash that pi
e}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8598532\charrsid16449734 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 dish, I was in bed then, I had to go down and wash that pie}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8598532\charrsid16449734 -
}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 dish before I could go to sleep.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Do you remember getting away with anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Oh - tried to.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 When was breakfast eaten in the morning?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Well about half past eight. Sometimes - you know what it is -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Who would be there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Oh me mum - was there. We only had porridge, that's all. Porridge every morning.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Would your father be there to have breakfast too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 No, he'd gone. Gone to work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 What time would he go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 
He - he'd go - he used to have to be to work at eight o'clock you see. And he'd get up about half past seven, have breakfast and off, and - and we'd get up eight o'clock, 'cos we didn't have to go to school 'til nine, and it was walking distance, you se
e. And - we had porridge and - mum was there to see us - off to school and that - was that. We'd come home at twelve o'clock, back again at half past one. Home at half past four.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Did your mother have breakfast with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 No, she used to have - sh
e never used to eat much breakfast, 'cos she was - you know, her chest and that, she used to - well I don't know what she did live on really. Used to give us our - our kiddies our breakfast.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Did you have anything different on any particular days like Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 OH we always used to have a roast on Sunday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 What about for breakfast?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 
Oh no. Well - of course - well of course there wasn't cornflakes so much then, it was porridge. Nearly all porridge and that. And - she used to make a lot of bread puddings. You know, for us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 This was at dinnertime?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 No. Well, in the week you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 When would you eat that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Tea time. And - suet puddings. Roly polys.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 This would be dinnertime?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Or - or teatime, 'cos we - we used to ha
ve our dinner - like - a bit of cold meat or something like that, dinnertimes 'cos we had a cooked tea when daddy came home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12858205 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 So at dinnertime was it just your mother and you children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4735342 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11080425\charrsid16449734 Children, yes, 'cos daddy used to take his sandwiches or whatever it is that he wanted and - then she used to cook when he came home.

